<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1436,1987,2013]" lastBlockId="23.[151,1437,151,321]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Knutson &amp; Orth. Russia-Cherny Mountains" authorityYear="1990" box="[151,391,1987,2013]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canadensis">
<emphasis box="[151,391,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Colobaea canadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been found only in the province of 
<collectingRegion box="[833,943,1987,2013]" country="Canada" name="Manitoba" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Manitoba</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[953,1041,1987,2013]" name="Canada" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Canada</collectingCountry>
. It most closely resembles 
<emphasis box="[1340,1436,1987,2013]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
C. 
<subSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="multiple">
<emphasis box="[151,213,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">bifasciella</emphasis>
in that both species have a dull, tomentose, setose, yellow frons; a similarly shaped head; two pairs of postalar setae; and 
<collectionCode box="[270,289,187,213]" country="Chile" name="Departamento de Geologia, Universidad de Chile" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">R</collectionCode>
<subScript attach="left" box="[288,296,205,219]" fontSize="6" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">1</subScript>
extending to the level of the r-m crossvein. These two species can be readily distinguished from each other, however, as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Knutson &amp; Orth. Russia-Cherny Mountains" authorityYear="1990" box="[362,519,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canadensis">
<emphasis box="[362,519,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">C. canadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a mainly shiny black body and unpatterned wings, whereas 
<taxonomicName box="[1242,1392,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bifasciella">
<emphasis box="[1242,1392,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">C. bifasciella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a yellow body with black markings and patterned wings. Nothing is known about the biology or immature stages of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Knutson &amp; Orth. Russia-Cherny Mountains" authorityYear="1990" box="[182,338,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Sciomyzidae" genus="Colobaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="canadensis">
<emphasis box="[182,338,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">C. canadensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</subSection>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
